node.text:
This exercise is included in my “Emotions 101” online course! The course is only available for purchase until May 2nd - so I highly recommend getting on this list. Click the link in my bio to get your spot!

Some disclaimers about these exercises:
- If you have a trauma history, experience flashbacks, have trouble with emotional regulation, experience suicidal ideation, or any other distressing symptoms, I highly recommend and suggest you practice these exercises with a trauma-informed, licensed therapist first.
- If at any point these exercises cause you to feel so overwhelmed or uncomfortable that you cannot continue, stop. Take note of any symptoms of distress: eyes fluttering, becoming hypervigilant, rapid or unsettled body movements, feeling overly uncomfortable, rapid heartbeat, overheating, or any other common signs of emotional flooding you experience.
- Before getting started, you may want to have some grounding items around you. Start in a comfortable space with things that help you remain calm. This may be a blanket, a photo, etc.
- Remember, you are the expert on your body and your experience. If something doesn’t work for you - that’s ok.
- Instead of judging or questioning yourself, try to stay with what is happening in your body. You can ask yourself questions like:
How am I noticing these feelings?
What is my experience like right now?
What is my body experiencing?
What am I wondering about?
What would help me feel safe right now?
- If you are really struggling with being still and reflecting on your internal experience, it may be best to practice mindfulness in other ways - like while eating, taking a shower, etc. to practice.

node.text:
@drcarolineleaf and @sitwithwhit discuss Dr. Leaf’s new book! We chat about the desire to find a “quick fix,” finding what works for you, and skilled mind management.

You can get @drcarolineleaf ‘s new book anywhere where books are sold! I hear it’s selling out quick - so get your copy soon! If you’re reading it, would love to hear your favorite parts.

node.title: Cleaning Up Your Mental Mess with @drcarolineleaf

node.text:
Back in my office @thecollaborativemiami today and thought I’d record my first IGTV video ever! Tackling the questions: Why do people stay in bad relationships?

Let’s talk about why it’s so hard to “just leave.”

Disclaimer: If you are being abused, emotionally or physically, you are not at fault. If the abuse is still going on and the other person has not made a deliberate effort to seek help and/or change their behavior, the relationship is not safe. These other signs are not possible until the abuse has stopped and the abuser takes responsibility for their actions and their role. I’m going to include some available resources in the caption of this video.

Leaving a toxic relationship can also be dangerous. I know most of us don’t think it would happen to us, but there are millions of reported cases of domestic violence a year in the US. Remember that your safety is most important. Here are some resources I recommend:
* Find a therapist in your area that specializes in abusive relationships.
* Support groups:
 Adult Children of Alcoholics
 ALANON
 Trauma Survivor Groups
 Domestic Violence Support Groups
* National Domestic Violence Hotline: 800-799-SAFE
* Books
 Gaslighting - Stephanie Sarkis
 The Gaslight Effect - Robin Stern
 Adult Children of Emotionally Immature Parents - Lindsey Gibson
* Domesticshelters.org has a lot of resources and book suggestions

PS. it’s EMAIL DAY! Make sure to vote for the topic in my stories and swipe up to get on my email list.

node.title: Why People Stay In Bad Relationships

node.accessibility_caption: Photo by whitney goodman lmft on August 30, 2021. May be an image of text that says 'Whitney Goodman, LMFT @sitwithwhit Ten things I've learned since becoming a parent [a thread]'.

node.text: 2 months in and here’s what I’ve learned. Wanted to share this here in case anyone else needed to hear this. #1-4 are particularly important to remember.

node.accessibility_caption: Photo by whitney goodman lmft on August 30, 2021. May be an image of text that says 'Whitney Goodman, LMFT @sitwithwhit Ten things I've learned since becoming a parent [a thread]'.

Photo by whitney goodman lmft on August 30, 2021. May be an image of text that says 'Whitney Goodman, LMFT @sitwithwhit 1. People are not being honest about what it's like to have children. think this is based in shame and fear.'.

Photo by whitney goodman lmft on August 30, 2021. May be an image of text that says 'Whitney Goodman, LMFT @sitwithwhit 2.1 thought that wouldn't struggle with anything related to parenthood if I did enough research, bought all all the right gadgets, and hired some help. This is absolutely false. I still struggled.'.

Photo by whitney goodman lmft on August 30, 2021. May be an image of text that says 'Whitney Goodman, LMFT @sitwithwhit 3. When I did hear people tell me it would be hard at times, found myself saying "oh that won't be me!" Telling yourself that you won't struggle and shouldn't be struggling only makes things harder.'.

Photo by whitney goodman lmft on August 30, 2021. May be an image of text that says 'Whitney Goodman, LMFT @sitwithwhit 4. Anyone that tells you parenting is always amazing, they haven't struggled with their physical and/o mental health, their marriage is perfect, and they wouldn't change a thing...is lying. I'm sorry, they just are.'.

Photo by whitney goodman lmft on August 30, 2021. May be an image of text that says 'Whitney Goodman, LMFT @sitwithwhit 5. Having a child will shine a light on everything in you that needs to be seen. learned I am absolutely incapable of accepting help and sitting still is very, very hard. Two things that are essential and pretty much mandatory Ûo a new parent.'.

Photo by whitney goodman lmft on August 30, 2021. May be an image of text that says 'Whitney Goodman, LMFT @sitwithwhit 6. Parenthood is the ultimate conflict of emotions. You can be exhausted, filled with anger at 2AM while your baby screams and love them with every fiber in your being. That anger and exhaustion can turn into a smile the second the laugh and look at you.'.

Photo by whitney goodman lmft on August 30, 2021. May be an image of text that says 'Whitney Goodman LMFT @sitwithwhit 7. There is nothing on this planet that will prepare you for the mental load of caring about and loving something this much. much. 8. You may constantly feel like you're failing, even when you're not.'.

Photo by whitney goodman lmft on August 30, 2021. May be an image of text that says 'Whitney Goodman, LMFT @sitwithwhit 9. People may get uncomfortable when you talk about the highs and lows of parenthood. You're not ungrateful. You love your child. 10. It's the greatest job and it is hard work. It is the best and the hardest thing I've ever done.'.

Photo by whitney goodman lmft on August 30, 2021. May be an image of one or more people and text that says 'Have you ever considered.... that the thing you're dealing with is actually so much harder because you're telling yourself it should be easy. @SITWITHWHIT'.

Photo by whitney goodman lmft on August 28, 2021. May be an image of text that says 'Whitney Goodman, LMFT @sitwithwhit Someone who is uncomfortable talking abou their own mental health and emotions will likely get uncomfortable when you talk about yours.'.

node.text:
Keep talking anyways !! I’m really comfortable talking about my mental health and I know when you do that people can be like what?? But if you’d talk about breaking your arm or someone having cancer…why can’t you also talk about this?

If someone gets uncomfortable, I promise it says way more about their attitudes towards what is acceptable and what isn’t. It also shows you how they feel about their own emotions and mental health.

Keep talking! This is one of the best ways you can help eliminate mental health stigma in a real way.

*yes there are people who will make your mental health worse when you share or who are not supportive people. Don’t share with them if it’s not productive. There’s a big difference between an unsafe person and an uncomfortable person. There are also places where it may not be productive to share. Big difference between talking about it at a dinner party and in an important meeting at work.**

node.accessibility_caption: Photo by whitney goodman lmft on August 27, 2021. May be an image of text that says 'Whitney Goodman, LMFT @sitwithwhit … We can take our insecurities & project that they're coming from other people. You feel unloveable and tell your partner they're not making you feel loved. You feel ugly & say that's why people aren't interested in you. You feel incompetent and that's why you didn't get a job.'.

node.text:
Have you ever gone out in an outfit you didn’t really feel comfortable in? You walk into the room and all the sudden it *seems* like everyone is staring at you. The only possible possible explanation you can come up with is that they think you look absolutely terrible and are all making fun of you.

We do this all the time. Assume that everyone else agrees with our insecurities and is actually causing them. If they didn’t stare, we wouldn’t feel ugly.

It’s usually a lot easier to say “you make me feel unloved” than admit you don’t feel lovable in general.

**and yes of course some people do instill and confirm insecurities in us. There are abusive relationships that are determined to make you feel bad. This post does not mean that that reality isn’t also true** This pattern is also very common for abuse survivors who are now in healthy relationships.

But, it’s worth asking yourself if you feel this way or if the other person is doing something to make you feel that way. Look at what they’re actually doing - could it have any other meaning?

node.accessibility_caption: Photo by whitney goodman lmft on August 26, 2021. May be an image of text that says 'Whitney Goodman, LMFT @sitwithwhit Many people who struggle with their mental health actually end up over functioning & doing too much. It's very hard to tell they're struggling. This may happen because they're in denial. being busy is a coping strategy distraction. letting people see their pain would be worse.'.

node.text: Raise your hand if this is you (🙋🏼‍♀️ I’m raising my hand).

node.accessibility_caption: Photo by whitney goodman lmft on August 26, 2021. May be an image of text.

node.text:
Sometimes we are assertive, kind, patient, etc. and people don’t see what we’re doing. They’re unable to view our kindness or our intention.

There are also times where we totally miss the mark and we hurt the person.

There will absolutely be situations where you did everything you could and the other person is choosing to hold onto their upset and you don’t feel like apologizing, explaining yourself, etc. THAT IS OK!

We have a choice in these moments. We can say:
1. This person is hell bent on misunderstanding me. I’m not going to continue to try to make them see my kindness.
2. I want to learn how to help this person better and I want to understand what is going wrong in our communication.

If you’re interested in repair and trying to understand/move forward…it’s helpful to use the phrases or some like them from the right column instead of the left.

node.accessibility_caption: Photo by whitney goodman lmft on August 25, 2021. May be an image of one or more people and text that says 'Whitney Goodman, LMFT @sitwithwhit Regret usually shows up when we use our current knowledge and competence to judge our past experiences. You didn't know then what you know now. It's likely impossible that you would've been able to contro the outcome the way you're telling yourself you could have.'.

node.text:
Just shared this in my stories, but thought it deserved a place here.

What is your biggest regret? Can you see how or why a previous version of you made that decision and have compassion for them?

node.accessibility_caption: Photo by whitney goodman lmft on August 25, 2021. May be an image of text that says 'Whitney Goodman, LMFT @sitwithwhit It's very hard to admit that we can still hurt someone even if.. we had good intentions it came from a good place we "mean well" we're just trying to help we didn't mean to.'.

node.text:
This is so hard to admit. It’s hard for me to admit. And honestly it’s one of the biggest barriers for honest communication/healing I see in relational therapy.

It’s also the response I get most often when I talk about toxic positivity. I meant well…I wanted to help…I was just trying to be nice… you’re taking it the wrong way etc.

The key to relational healing is understanding that sometimes we have to accept something didn’t land the right way even if we meant well. This often means figuring out where things went wrong, talking about the trigger, seeking understanding, and working to do better. It’s hard and it takes a lot of humility.

Do you struggle with this?

node.accessibility_caption: Photo by whitney goodman lmft on August 24, 2021. May be an image of 1 person and text that says 'Whitney Goodman, LMFT @sitwithwhit If your parent's report of their emotions didn't match their behavior e.g., they're crying and saying everything is great), it might be hard for you to trust when other people tell you how they feel.'.

node.text: If you’re constantly checking in on other people and asking if they’re ok or how they’re doing, it might be worth looking back at your childhood. Did your caregivers or family members act like everything was ok when it wasn’t? Did their outward expression of emotion not really make sense?

node.accessibility_caption: Photo by whitney goodman lmft on August 24, 2021. May be an image of text.

node.text:
What other forms of toxic positivity have you heard about parenting?

Should I do a post on what you can say instead?

node.accessibility_caption: Photo by whitney goodman lmft on August 23, 2021. May be an image of text that says 'things to say when you don't know what to say @SITWITHWHIT "I'm here for you." "This is hard." "I don't know what to say, but I'm going to figure out how to help you." "I don't know what to say, but I'm not going anywhere." "There are probably no words that will make this better and wish there were." just want you to know you." Ask open ended questions about their experience "I'm here for you and I'm listening." love you and care about'.

node.text: And sometimes silence and just being there really is enough.

node.accessibility_caption: Photo by whitney goodman lmft on August 21, 2021. May be an image of text that says 'Whitney Goodman, LMFT @sitwithwhit When I realized that not everyone shows that they care in the same way I do, it helped me -stop resenting people. -stop blaming people. -understand there are so to show you care. -teach people what I like and want in moments of distress. many ways'.

node.text:
Yesterday I posted about thank you notes and it made me think about this realization I had. So many of you said that you didn’t write them, didn’t think to write them, would never expect one from someone, or that people who didn’t receive one from you were upset.

This is such a perfect example of how we all have different ways to show how we care. And how we can all draw different conclusions when someone doesn’t perform in what we think is a “caring” way.

In my family, we don’t get each other birthday gifts. I’ve never sent my siblings or parents a birthday card. When I married my husband, I noticed his family members always send cards.  This isn’t something I was used to doing and it would be so so easy for someone to think “wow, they didn’t even send a card!” if this is how they show love or care.

I’m horrible about checking in with people but I’m thinking about them in my head all the time. I would do anything for anyone when they needed it, but I’m known to get stuck in my own head during the day to day. For so many of us (including me!) it’s not until someone shows us how to show we care that we’re able to do that. We think we’re doing it because it’s our way of showing. And, a lot of it that person doesn’t even see!

Instead of looking for them to show up exactly how you do, look for how they show that they care.

Does your mom provide for you in certain ways, but maybe they’re not the best with emotional support?

Is your sibling the first person you rely on in an emergency but you can’t get them to answer your texts on a normal day?

How do they show they care?

When we stop trying to get people to offer us things they cannot and focus on what they can and are offering, life gets a lot easier.

And yes, as always, this is not an excuse for abuse and you can always decide “I don’t like what this person can give me” and walk away. This post is for people who want to stay in a relationship.
